{"title": "Evidence Dungeon", "content": "The Evidence Dungeon is the lair of the villain, which is full of all the things a good villain needs to do their work...and to be charged with said work when the police find it.\n\nThe defining feature of an Evidence Dungeon is the expositional shit lying around that any sane person would hide or dispose of immediately. It's a place that is not only the villain's lair but is also where all the incriminating evidence is kept. This may make for a very foolish criminal, or just the right kind of delusional mind that would commit the crimes in the first place.\n\nThe Evidence Dungeon combines Chronic Evidence Retention Syndrome, the villain's lair and a healthy dollop of stupidity. It can overlap with conspiracy theories, the proof of their insanity and gruesome bad guy trophies. If the evidence is part of a creepy collection, you might be in The Doll Episode.\n\nIt is the inverse of an Orgy of Evidence which is done intentionally to mislead. An Evidence Dungeon is unintentionally discovered, a convenient dumping ground of evidence and plot clues for The Protagonist.\n\nDiffers from Chronic Evidence Retention Syndrome which can be more specific, for example, keeping a single incriminating note or weapon. Also not the same as a Room Full of Crazy which proves insanity but not necessarily guilt. For a Serial Killer, the place can be his Torture Cellar. The Big Board can be a non-insane version of Evidence Dungeon.\n\nA Smug Snake or The Starscream might collect an Evidence Dungeon, too arrogant to believe that they would be caught. A Big Bad or Big Bad Wannabe has far-ranging plans with the correspondingly abundant evidence. Often it is the Serial Killer either collecting trophies of their work or too insane to realize all the clues just laying around.\n\nA detective/doctor/family member can stumble across Evidence Dungeons, shortly followed by some time Alone with the Psycho. Often this leads to an attempt on the discoverer's life by the owner of the room. These rooms can be also be susceptible to cases of vanishing evidence as well.\n\nTrope Namer is from Episode 8 of The Flop House podcast.", "url": "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/EvidenceDungeon", "media_links": ["/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/WesternAnimation/SouthPark", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Manga/PanoramaOfHell", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/ComicBook/FiftyTwo", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/ComicBook/BoosterGold", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/ComicBook/JohnnyTheHomicidalManiac", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/Watchmen", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/ComicBook/SinCity", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Disney/Zootopia", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/IKnowWhoKilledMe", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Franchise/TheTexasChainsawMassacre", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Franchise/Saw", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/Se7en", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/OneHourPhoto", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/Unbreakable", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/Gothika", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/KissTheGirls", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/MinorityReport", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/REC", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/Memento", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/TheSkeletonKey", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/PulpFiction", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/HouseOf1000Corpses", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/Hostel", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/ThePoughkeepsieTapes", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/HotFuzz", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/DeadCalm", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/CaptainAmericaCivilWar", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/TheSilenceOfTheLambs", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/TheMillenniumTrilogy", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/AmericanPsycho", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/Unique", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/TheDresdenFiles", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/WhiteNight", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Series/Hannibal", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Series/Bones", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Series/Quantico", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Series/TerminatorTheSarahConnorChronicles", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Series/TheWire", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Series/MastersOfHorror", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Series/BuffyTheVampireSlayer", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Series/MissionImp